Diagnosis.

Lipinia sekayuensis


sp. nov.

can be distinguished from all other species of 

Lipinia

by having the combination of an adult SVL of 42.3 mm; six supralabials; five infralabials; four supraoculars; prefrontals widely separated; two loreals; fused frontoparietals; lower eyelids bearing a large, transparent disc; 
21
midbody scale rows; 
56
paravertertebral scale rows; 
65
ventral scale rows; enlarged, precloacal scales; 
10
subdigital lamellae on the third finger; 
11, 15
, and seven lamellae on the third, fourth, and fifth toes, respectively; distal subdigital lamellae keeled; a median row of slightly enlarged, subcaudal scales; a generally unicolor, dark-brown dorsum bearing nine very faint, diffuse, darker stripes; and an external ear opening replaced by a scaly, auditory depression (

Table 
1

).
